Classifying Images from the CANDELS survey Machine Learning Techniques

This internship explored the accuracy of using a convolutional neural network to distinguish between images to identify possible galaxies within the dataset.

A convolutional neural network (aka CNN or CovNet) is a machine learning algorithm based on the neurons in our brains. It uses layers as building blocks to analyse typically 2D image data, though other dimensions of image data have been used as well. Each layer is called a ‘hidden layer’, and can invuolve 4 types of layers: a convulsion layer for inputting the image, a pooling layer for outputting the image, a normalisation layer for the activation processes and a fully connected dense layer, typically used at the end of a network. Additional layers may also be added for optimisation and regularisation purposes, such as a dropout layer, which drops certain ‘neurons’ between each layer to prevent overfitting.

The first week consisted of reading the paper 'Galaxy Zoo CANDELS data release', Simmons et al., 2017, to understand how crowdsourcing worked for Galaxy Zoo CANDELS, but importantly, to gain an understanding of how the voting fractions classifies an image into a star or a galaxy.

The rest of the week was spent on looking into tutorials into classification algorithms. This was done by training the MNIST fashion catalogue using the Tensorflow tutorial. This took about a day. However, even though the training was clear, I didn't learn very much from it, as it used a preloaded model that I didn't have and it didn't show how to load your own images, which was my case.

I then realised that to upload 6GB of images online just to retrieve it again offline wasn't practical. So I made a copy of all the images (given via a USB drive) into the hard drive.

The plan was to use the .fits.gz file to create a /csv file of all the stars, galaxies and other objects into 3 different .csv files, one for stars, one for galaxies, and one for other objects (named bright_stars, extended_sources, and non_es respectively). This was done via the following:

Images to CSV:

  • The first step was to download all image files via GZ_Cd (I got mine through Brooke), make a back up copy of it.
  • Then obtain the .fits.gz (it should be a zip) file for all the images in a table format.
  • Save it in a sensible place.
  • Then using Topcat, click open > filestore browser > [your sensible file location] (in this case it's Desktop) > Alice on the Mac
  • Make sure that you haven't corrupted the file beforehand or it will not open.
  • Click on on of the table icons (I think it's the 9 grid table icon) to see a tick list of all table names. Click on untick all icon, and retick the Hubble_IMG_ID (something like that?). Double click to 'rename', but actually copy the names for later use. Do the same for "WFC3_F160w_magnitude", but don't tick the box. This should just give you a column of names for the images.
  • Click on the weird Venn diagram (which looks more like a pie or a circle inside a circle than a venn diagram) to configure subsets.
  • Create a new subset using the green plus sign. Give it a name, and give it a condition for one of the catagories using the conditions listed in the publication (Galaxy Zoo CANSELS data release, Simmons et al., 2017)
  • Close that, then click on the grid with lightning icon. Find 'Display Image' and tick that. This makes sure that your image will show up as you click on an entry in the column.
  • Depending on the condition, it should give you a list of stars galaxies or unclassifiable images. Have a quick flick through to make sure that they're mostly right (note, when I say quick, it will still take a long time because there are lots of images). When you're done, and you're ehappy with the images around, save the list of images that met the criteria you set before as a .csv file.

Using this list, I can then move the files with matching names into their relevant folders. I created the three folders in the directory, and tried to write a python code to move everything over. That didn't work well.

Through a meeting, I got informed about Awk, which is very good at moving files and working with .csv files. So I did as follows:

CSV to separate folders:

  • Create some new folders, each with the names of the category of images the folder will contain.
  • Open the terminal.
  • You'll need Awk for the following:
  • Type the command (in a single line):
  • Where $1 is 'substitute name from your .csv column', the ../bright stars is your path to the folder you want to move the images to, and ../../bright_star_list.csv is the location of your .csv column. | head makes sure that it prints the first 5 lines.
  • Make sure you modify the parts in '{ }'. This is because Awk basically prints commands in the command line repeatedly via your list of csv files. It uses the same command, but substitutes the file names. That's why the | head is needed, to check if the command is correct (currently it's not!! This is because I copied an older, less correct one in terms of the stuff inside {}, since the correct one, was unfortunately, not saved.)
  • Save the correct command here! (So you don't make the same mistake again)
  • With the correct command, run it to move your files for one category.
  • Edit the path and the .csv file to the original command to move the other category to another file.
  • Check through your files to see if everything is done properly. If not, make a copy of the backup copy, and repeat this section, checking for errors.

As one can see, the program was not producing consistent results. After a bit of research, I found that the use of a seed can help. This is what I noted in my notes:

Ok, I changed the seed to '1337' instead of '1', and turned multiprocessing off, as suggested in one of the posts. Why '1337'? Because it's not 1. Ok, being serious, I changed it in the hopes that the results will be more consistent, because sometimes, putting 1 in a random number generator is not a good idea, and one of the comments just happened to use 1337, so I went with it. Hope this goes well!

I then further changed some parameters after filtering thorugh possible causes of fluctuations on stack exchange and GitHub. One suggestion was to turn multiprocessing off, so I did, and made a note in my log:

For ease of comprehension, just so that my life is easier when debugging. And yes, I have taken out multiprocessing=True. I have a feeling that it might have provided some noise to the program. So the trade off for a slightly slower program (not by that much actually) is a better output. I have also altered batch size from 32 to 128 (apparently, the wiggle room in loss is related to batch size. Larger batch = more wiggles in loss).

This lead to a more accurate graph, which was good news:
